Optimal denaturation conditions may vary depending on the thermal cycler and tubes used. Ranges from 10-30 seconds at 94 ºC can be used.





False negatives may result when:


• Tail or ear samples deteriorate before processing \(do not leave the samples at room temperature for too long);


• Residual alcohol is present;


• DNA is dried longer than 10 minutes and is inefficiently resuspended;


• Excess protein inhibits the PCR; 


• The DNA pellet dislodges during decanting.





A false positive in the water-only sample indicates that contamination has occurred.





The LA enzyme is very sensitive to the DNA concentration; too much DNA inhibits the reaction\!
